Bike Sharing data exploration Part 1¶

by David Babalola¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset has records 183,412 rides and has 16 features. There are 7 columns that are floats, 2 of them are ints, while 7 are object (strings).

user_type: Subscriber, Customer \ member_gender: Male, Female, Other \ bike_share_for_all_trip: Yes, No

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in understanding which features affect the duration and ride distance (to be engineered) of the ride.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that start_longitude and start_latitude, member_gender, user_type, and member_birth_year will have effect on each bike ride's duration:

Utility functions¶

In [17]:
def createCountPlot(df, variable, color=sb.color_palette()[0], hue = None, palette = None):
    """
    Given a particular dataframe and variable, this function plots a count plot of the values therein
    
    Parameters:
        df (Dataframe): The dataset
        variable (string): name of the column
    """
    # Set dimensions
    plt.figure(figsize=[14, 8])

    # Plot countplot
    sb.countplot(data=df, x=variable, edgecolor='black', color=color);
    
    variableText = variable.split('_')
    variableText = " ".join(variableText).title()
    
    # Add title with formatting
    plt.title(f'Distribution of {variableText}'.title(), fontsize=13, weight='bold')
    
    # Add x label with formatting
    plt.xlabel(variableText.title(), fontsize=10, weight='bold')
    
    # Add y label with formatting
    plt.ylabel('Frequency', fontsize=10, weight='bold')
In [18]:
import math
def calculateHaversine(currentRow):
    """This function returns the haversine given the latitudes and longitudes for the start and end.
    The Haversine Formula computes the great-circle distance, the shortest distance between two 
    points on the surface of a Sphere). 
    
    Parameters:
        currentRow (Series): The row that you want to calculate the havesine for
    Return:
        haversine (float): The haversine calculated from the start/end longitudes and latitudes in metres
    """
    start_station_longitude = math.radians(currentRow['start_station_longitude'])
    end_station_longitude = math.radians(currentRow['end_station_longitude'])
    start_station_latitude = math.radians(currentRow['start_station_latitude'])
    end_station_latitude = math.radians(currentRow['end_station_latitude'])

    # Haversine formula
    diffOfLongitude = end_station_longitude - start_station_longitude
    diffOfLatitude = end_station_latitude - start_station_latitude

    a = math.sin(diffOfLatitude / 2)**2 + math.cos(start_station_latitude) * math.cos(end_station_latitude) * math.sin(diffOfLongitude / 2)**2
    c = 2 * math.asin(math.sqrt(a))

    # Radius of earth in kilometers. Use 3956 for miles
    r = 6371

    # calculate the result
    return(c * r * 1000)

Conclusions¶

In this Project, I explored bike-sharing data set with information about individual rides made covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

After data collection, I started by doing some preliminary data wrangling (dropping NaN and unneeded columns, converting column types). I then proceeded to explore the data. I found out that ride distance has a significant correlation with duration (as expected). I found that most Subscribers have a shorter ride distance and duration. I also found that males and females have similar distribution in terms of ride distance and duration while Other genders have a slightly higher average ride duration and distance. Furthermore, Male Customers were observed to have a larger range of ride duration.

The bike share for all trip program has no effect on ride duration.

Most of the members were born between 1980 and 2000. Furthermore, I found that of the first 50 bikes with highest number of rides, most of the riders were done by Males, Subscribers, and people that were not part of the bike share for all trip program. We observed that most of the members were born between 1980 and 2000.
